# ATT Rewards & Loyalty Friction Analysis Report

Analysis of 16 customer calls related to ATT Rewards & Loyalty programs reveals a single, highly impactful theme: Rewards & Loyalty Management. This theme accounts for 3.2% of all analyzed calls and is driven by systemic issues across digital, operational, communication, and policy dimensions. The top 3 issues by call volume are: difficulty changing cashback redemption preferences (7 calls, 43.75%), confusion over merchant category codes affecting bonus points (4 calls, 25%), and discrepancies in welcome bonus crediting (2 calls, 12.5%). The dominant driver for these issues is digital, with contributing factors from operations, communication, and policy. A total of 7 quick wins were identified, indicating a high potential for rapid improvement. All identified issues are highly preventable through improved digital transparency, proactive communication, and streamlined internal policies.

---

| Theme | Impact | Ease | Priority | Quadrant |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Rewards & Loyalty | 8.25 | 7.0 | 7.75 | quick_win |

---

### Digital
- Enhance the findability of redemption preference settings within the rewards dashboard. Provide clear options for customers to select and manage their preferred cashback method.
- Improve transparency around merchant category coding and its impact on bonus eligibility. Educate customers on how transactions are categorized.
- Provide clear, real-time tracking of welcome bonus progress and transparent communication of all qualifying criteria.
- Implement proactive communication and visibility for tier status changes and qualification progress.
- Provide digital visibility into the status and expected posting of anniversary bonus points.
- Improve transparency around category bonus eligibility and any associated caps or exclusions.
- Implement a digital tracking mechanism for points transfers to external partners.

### Operations
- No specific recommendations for Operations were identified as dominant drivers.

### Communication
- No specific recommendations for Communication were identified as dominant drivers.

### Policy
- No specific recommendations for Policy were identified as dominant drivers.

